Could be a good image but at a noticeably low resolution, or high resolution but with significant flaws. Lighting might be severely backlit or poorly exposed. Image might be good but the bird is extremely small in the frame or mostly obscured.     1 Star: Very poor quality. Observation Details: Fascinating bird to study. Located with the other American Coots at the beach. This bird had a greatly retracted red-shield giving way to a yellowish base and sparse reddish marks towards the top. As far as I am concerned this is neither a vagrant nor particularly rare. It just happens to be a variant (likely male (Sibley et. al)) in the coot population. Although this is not a "pure" white-shielded bird, I put it as this designation to separated it for study from the slew of other coot reports.   A note of personal curiosity: why does eBird have options for some field-identifiable forms but not others? (e.g. "green" Pine Siskin and "bar-breasted" Upland Goose, but not "storm" American Wigeon or "blue" Snow Goose?). Is there a morphological/taxonomical difference, is it for tracking populations, or is it completely arbitrary?

Media notes: NOTES: 59094;"night; a good variety of territorial calls; " (WWHG)  [This recording begins with series of calls by at least two different birds (0:15-0:37, 0:46-0:52) that are similar to the series in LNS #2804.  Between these is another series that probably represents the Perturbation Call discussed in BNA (0:40-0:45; like LNS #2810).  The second and third parts of the recording contain harsh, nasal calls that I suspect are Warning Notes by a female (0:52-1:11, 1:13-1:29).  The fourth part begins with a decapitated series that I suspect is similar to those at the beginning of the recording (1:37-1:40), this followed by various Recognition Calls given in the background.  The fifth part begins with three calls similar to those in the second and third parts (2:03-2:08), followed by a series like those in the first part (2:09-2:16), and finally, ending with three Recognition Calls (2:17-2:20).  The sixth part begins with two series of calls (the first decapitated) and ends with four Recognition Calls, apparently given by a female.  The seventh part appears to combine the harsh, nasal calls with "puk" Recognition Calls (possibly given in parent-young contact).  The eighth part highlights more of the harsh, nasal calls.  The ninth part begins with two Recognition Calls by a female (3:27-3:28), followed by two nasal calls (3:30-3:33), and ends with some Recognition Calls in the background (3:34, 3:43-3:47).  The last part contains exclusively Recognition Calls, apparently by both a male and a female.  Quality added (2-1, 2 - the first part is the BEST) - CAM - 9 March 2005]. Other Behaviors: Advertise.

Observation Details: Several dozen, not counted. Made a recording of one or two at the northeast corner of Cell 3. It begins with higher-pitched calls from two coots (or a coot and an unseen Common Gallinule), then the coot makes a series of grunting sounds, followed by odd percussive or flapping sounds (the source of which I couldn't see), followed by more grunting sounds at a lower pitch than the first ones.

Observation Details: *Late; after finding no coots last night here after checking carefully, I have to wonder if I missed this bird or not. This individual sets the late date for the pond by four days; photos

In cove directly across from non-motorized launch.  How I count:  I count first 10, then 20 and group then into a perceptible size and continue counting in groups of 20.  Once I hit 100 I estimate the entire group of coots.  The interesting thing this day was that I kayaked up the Bill Williams River earlier and coots were virtually non-existent but when I approached the cove across from launch, a mass of coots was present.  I believe my estimate is conservative.
Only adults seen this year; two pairs had young during GBD 2015. This year, two were in water, one sitting on shore and walked toward me.

Media notes: NOTES: "Bird was vocalizing from cattail marsh..."[As far as I can determine, the bulk of this recording combines the "Twitter" Calls of chicks (following Cosens, S. E. 1981. Can. J. Zool. 59: 1921-1928) with Recognition Calls by an adult, apparently a female (following BNA).  Also heard in the background at 0:43-0:46 is the same whistled call highlighted in LNS #2810 (this call-type remains unidentified).  I suspect the series at 2:04-2:18 represents Warning Calls by the female parent, but most of the part after the internal announcement appears to represent the calls of the chicks with only intermittent Recognition Calls by the female (4:10-4:27, 5:16-5:25, 5:30, 5:59, 6:02, 6:13, 6:35, 6:46, 6:54, 6:55).  The Recognition Calls at 7:15-7:33 appear to have instead been given by a male.  Beginning at about 7:13, there appear to be "Squawks" by the chicks in addition to the "Twitters" heard throughout the recording; there are also a few more Recognition Calls by the adult(s).  I believe the single quacks at 5:25, 5:35, and 5:48 are those of Anas strepera.  Quality changed from 2 to 2-3, 2-1 (BEST parts at 0:19-0:32 (Twittering and Recognition Calls), 2:04-2:18 (Warning [?] Calls), 4:19-4:27 (Twittering and Recognition Calls), 5:19-5:25 (Recognition Calls), 7:55-8:21 (Squawks))- CAM - 8 March 2005]). Habitat: Wetland.

Media notes: NOTES: [Seven examples of a high, clear "phuk" that, based on BNA account, appears to represent the Recognition Call of a male bird.  Quality added (2-1) - CAM - 4 March 2005]. Other Behaviors: Emit Alarm, Social Context: Mixed. Habitat: Wetland, Freshwater, Pond.

Three tock/bark-like notes, followed by several grunt-like notes. The gap between segments is exactly 1:14 of time. I had started an announcement for the initial calls, then the bird started with the quieter grunts.  It's possible that the grunt-like notes were from both individuals together but I never saw the second individual join this one. There were two individuals foraging, mostly silently, separated by about 10 m, at least when I could see or hear both. Same individual as ML287213031, different individual than ML287215881.

Observation Details: Same amount today - 3 adult pairs, one with 6 chicks, one with 2 (eggs still in nest as well), and one with eggs on nest. 2 other juvenile birds at pond too.  Pair with new chicks was out on the pond actively diving and feeding, didn't show much interest in the nest until a few minutes later. One adult came back over and sat back on it. Other parent was very aggressive to any other birds there, swam half the length of the pond (leaving its own chicks unguarded for a good minute in the middle of the pond) to attack a juvenile coot.   Other pair at the southern end of the pond were still sitting on their nest, so presumably still have eggs.   Pair with 6 chicks is still staying at the Northern end of the pond near the common gallinules.

Observation Details: Returning for the season, and sadly overlooked ...   1045 – the first Coot of the day!! Spotted in the smaller pond alongside his Red-shielded buddy; foraging together. At one point, it handed over some grassy mush to his buddy. Courtship?   Looks just like a Red-shielded American Coot, but instead of a maroon forehead shield, this White-shielded American Coot has an all-white shield that extends higher to the forehead. Similar shield of a Eurasian Coot, but subspecies differentiate in their bill coloring, where the White-shielded, similarly to the Red-shielded, has a dark subterminal band on their bills vs the Eurasian bill which is all white.  Super cute coot!! :)) #TeamCoot

Observation Details: Continuing, American Coot, first reported by Brandy J. Black waterfowl, almost entirely white, pointed beak with darkish color circling near the tip, white tail converts, red shield above the beak. I tried to check every bird on the pond. I checked the spot that Brandy photographed the coot the evening before. I waited at slip 30 for a few minutes, checking for the coot and counting waterfowl. No coot. I tried walking to the shore, maybe I could see it from there. I flushed a brown passerine and a snipe from the reeds. I knew the snipe but couldn't catch what the other was. Just then the coot appeared, and my attention instantly focused there. I felt the same level of excitement as when I saw the coot in Sitka in March. A Fairbanks kid, I never grew up with coots, so their looks and behavior are new for me. This time the bird was diving down to get algae and also eating other aquatic plants. Very satisfying time with the coot! Thanks to Brandy for the great finds on Friday!

Observation Details: An incubating adult Coot was sitting on the nest just about 3-4 metres west of where I was standing along the edge of the road (Latitude: 53.33628 N & Longitude:109.97889 W).  The nest was made of marsh vegetation including dead reeds and twigs.  Curiously, a single strand of barb wire seemed to go under the nest and appeared to be actually stabilizing it.  The bird sat on the nest while I photographed it.  However, I made one move too close or too abruptly sending the adult Coot left the nest.  This allowed me to see into the nest and count 7 eggs.

ML: Unbroken cut with internal recordist announcement gain change.  BNA: Three different calls are given here.  The "horn-like" toots given thoughout the early part of the recording (0:04-1:00) may be the Perturbation Calls described in BNA account, if indeed they were given by Fulica americana and not Gallinula chloropus (though I suspect that they were given by a coot).  The harsher, more nasal calls at 0:45-0:54 were definitely given by Fulica, but it is unclear whether they are Alarm Calls or Warning Calls.  Finally, there is a series of what appear to be Recognition Calls at 1:01-1:06.  (CAM - 9 March 2005).

Media notes: NOTES: "assorted territorial calls + rushes; Also: red-winged blackbird, gadwall, redheads, chorus frogs, green-winged teal, shoveler, killdeer; Nagra 60-301;40" reflector" WWHG[The first part of this recording begins with a decapitated series similar to that in LNS #2804 (0:14-0:19), this followed by what appears to be a series of the Perturbation Calls described in BNA (0:20-0:23).  The second part begins with another series like that beginning the first part (0:32-0:39), this followed by a series of "tack-tack" calls alternating with splashing around (0:41-0:53), possibly given by an unreceptive female.  I do not hear any calls by this species in the third part.  The calls in the fourth and fifth parts all appear to represent Recognition Calls (1:27-2:07, 2:09-2:15), apparently given by a female.  The sixth part contains splashing, a good series of harsh notes much like that in LNS #2804 (2:24-2:30), followed by a similar set in the background (2:30-2:33), a series of what I suspect are Perturbation Calls not quite like any that I have heard to date (2:33-2:36), and then a more normal series that appears to represent Perturbation Calls (2:36-2:40).  The seventh part begins with Recognition Calls (2:52-2:57), followed by two sets of harsh calls (3:00-3:08, 3:22-3:27), and then more Recognition Calls (3:31-3:36).  Calls in the eighth part all appear to represent Recognition Calls (3:40-4:05), those in the ninth part another harsh series (4:18-4:26), and those in the parts 10, 11, and 12 again Recognition Calls (4:27-4:51, 4:52-5:14 (with GOOD examples of Aythya americana in the background), 5:22-5:42 (again with Aythya)).  Quality added (2, 1-2 - BEST part at 2:20-2:43) - CAM - 9 March 2005]. Other Behaviors: Advertise.

Observation Details: Continuing; possibly 2.  Similar to the Red-shielded Coot but has a extended white shield, where the callus on the upper portion of the shield is mostly white with yellow, and a tiny bit of maroon. After some research with other documented images on Ebird for White-shielded Coots, the degree of maroon is not uncharacteristic for this morphology. However, I will leave it to the experts since this is the first time I have encountered one that did not have a clean, white callus.    1043 - Observed from the western shoreline, associating with the Red-shielded, including in what looked to be egging/instigating a rumble between 2 Red-shielded Coots.

Same amount today - 3 adult pairs, one with 6 chicks, one with 2 (eggs still in nest as well), and one with eggs on nest. 2 other juvenile birds at pond too.  Pair with new chicks was out on the pond actively diving and feeding, didn't show much interest in the nest until a few minutes later. One adult came back over and sat back on it. Other parent was very aggressive to any other birds there, swam half the length of the pond (leaving its own chicks unguarded for a good minute in the middle of the pond) to attack a juvenile coot.   Other pair at the southern end of the pond were still sitting on their nest, so presumably still have eggs.   Pair with 6 chicks is still staying at the Northern end of the pond near the common gallinules.

Observation Details: Returning for the season, and sadly overlooked ...   1045 – the first Coot of the day!! Spotted in the smaller pond alongside his Red-shielded buddy; foraging together. At one point, it handed over some grassy mush to his buddy. Courtship?   Looks just like a Red-shielded American Coot, but instead of a maroon forehead shield, this White-shielded American Coot has an all-white shield that extends higher to the forehead. Similar shield of a Eurasian Coot, but subspecies differentiate in their bill coloring, where the White-shielded, similarly to the Red-shielded, has a dark subterminal band on their bills vs the Eurasian bill which is all white.  Super cute coot!! :)) #TeamCoot
